<subsection xml:id="subsec-expressing-numbers-in-index-form" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Expressing numbers in index form</title>
    <p>
        Index form means writing a number using a base and an exponent (also called an index or power).
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Base}</m> is the number that is multiplied by itself, and <m>\textbf{exponent}</m> (or index) tells how many times the base is used in the multiplication.
    </p>
    <p>
        A number in index form is written as <m>a^n</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>n</m> is the exponent.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{To express a number in index form, you can follow these steps:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        1. Identify the base of the number you want to express in index form.
    </p>
    <p>
        2. Determine the exponent (or index), which is the number of times the base is multiplied by itself to obtain the original number.
    </p>
    <p>
        3. Write the number in the form <m>a^n</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>n</m> is the exponent.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, the number <m>8</m> can be expressed in index form as <m>2^3</m>, since <m>2 \times 2 \times 2 = 8</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Expressing numbers in index form is useful for simplifying calculations, especially when dealing with large numbers or when performing operations like multiplication and division.
    </p>
